# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: do-178c
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The basic idea of any software development model is that each step of the design process has outputs called "deliverables." If the deliverables are tested for correctness and fixed, then normal human mistakes can not easily grow into dangerous or expensive problems.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Most manufacturers follow the waterfall model to coordinate the design product, but almost all explicitly permit earlier work to be revised.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The result is more often closer to a spiral model.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] For an overview of embedded software see embedded system and software development models.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The rest of this article assumes familiarity with that information, and discusses differences between commercial embedded systems and commercial development models.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Since most avionics manufacturers see software as a way to add value without adding weight, the importance of embedded software in avionic systems is increasing.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Most modern commercial aircraft with auto-pilots use flight computers and so called flight management systems (FMS) that can fly the aircraft without the pilot's active intervention during certain phases of flight.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Also under development or in production are unmanned vehicles: missiles and drones which can take off, cruise and land without airborne pilot intervention.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] In many of these systems, failure is unacceptable.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The reliability of the software running in airborne vehicles (civil or military) is shown by the fact that most airborne accidents occur due to manual errors.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Unfortunately reliable software is not necessarily easy to use or intuitive, poor user interface design has been a contributing cause of many aerospace accidents and deaths.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Due to safety requirements, most nations regulate avionics, or at least adopt standards in use by a group of allies or a customs union.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The three regulatory organizations that most affect international aviation development are the U.S., the E.U. and Russia.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] In the U.S., avionic and other aircraft components have safety and reliability standards mandated by the Federal Aviation Regulations, Part 25 for Transport Airplanes, Part 23 for Small Airplanes, and Parts 27 and 29 for Rotorcraft.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] These standards are enforced by "designated engineering representatives" of the FAA who are usually paid by a manufacturer and certified by the FAA.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] In the European Union the IEC describes "recommended" requirements for safety-critical systems, which are usually adopted without change by governments.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] A safe, reliable piece of avionics has a "CE Mark." The regulatory arrangement is remarkably similar to fire safety in the U.S. and Canada.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The government certifies testing laboratories, and the laboratories certify both manufactured items and organizations.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Essentially, the oversight of the engineering is outsourced from the government and manufacturer to the testing laboratory.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] To assure safety and reliability, national regulatory authorities (e.g. the FAA, CAA, or DOD) require software development standards.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Some representative standards include MIL-STD-2167 for military systems, or RTCA DO-178B and its successor DO-178C for civil aircraft.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The regulatory requirements for this software can be expensive compared to other software, but they are usually the minimum that is required to produce the necessary safety.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The main difference between avionics software and other embedded systems is that the actual standards are often far more detailed and rigorous than commercial standards, usually described by documents with hundreds of pages.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] It is usually run on a real time operating system.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Since the process is legally required, most processes have documents or software to trace requirements from numbered paragraphs in the specifications and designs to exact pieces of code, with exact tests for each, and a box on the final certification checklist.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] This is specifically to prove conformance to the legally mandated standard.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Deviations from a specific project to the processes described here can occur due to usage of alternative methods or low safety level requirements.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Almost all software development standards describe how to perform and improve specifications, designs, coding, and testing (See software development model).
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Projects with substantial human interfaces are usually prototyped or simulated.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The videotape is usually retained, but the prototype retired immediately after testing, because otherwise senior management and customers can believe the system is complete.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] A major goal is to find human-interface issues that can affect safety and usability.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Safety-critical avionics usually have a hazard analysis.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The early stages of the project, already have at least a vague idea of the main parts of the project.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] An engineer then takes each block of a block diagram and considers the things that could go wrong with that block, and how they affect the system as a whole.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Subsequently, the severity and probability of the hazards are estimated.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The problems then become requirements that feed into the design's specifications.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Projects involving military cryptographic security usually include a security analysis, using methods very like the hazard analysis.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] As soon as the engineering specification is complete, writing the maintenance manual can start.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] A maintenance manual is essential to repairs, and of course, if the system can't be fixed, it will not be safe.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] There are several levels to most standards.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] A low-safety product such as an in-flight entertainment unit (a flying TV) may escape with a schematic and procedures for installation and adjustment.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] A navigation system, autopilot or engine may have thousands of pages of procedures, inspections and rigging instructions.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Documents are now (2003) routinely delivered on CD-ROM, in standard formats that include text and pictures.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] One of the odder documentation requirements is that most commercial contracts require an assurance that system documentation will be available indefinitely.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The normal commercial method of providing this assurance is to form and fund a small foundation or trust.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The trust then maintains a mailbox and deposits copies (usually in ultrafiche) in a secure location, such as rented space in a university's library (managed as a special collection), or (more rarely now) buried in a cave or a desert location.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] These are usually much like those in other software development models.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] A crucial difference is that requirements are usually traced as described above.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] In large projects, requirements-traceability is such a large expensive task that it requires large, expensive computer programs to manage it.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The code is written, then usually reviewed by a programmer (or group of programmers, usually independently) that did not write it originally (another legal requirement).
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Special organizations also usually conduct code reviews with a checklist of possible mistakes.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] When a new type of mistake is found it is added to the checklist, and fixed throughout the code.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The code is also often examined by special programs that analyze correctness (Static code analysis), such as SPARK examiner for the SPARK (a subset of the Ada programming language) or lint for the C-family of programming languages (primarily C, though).
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The compilers or special checking programs like "lint" check to see if types of data are compatible with the operations on them, also such tools are regularly used to enforce strict usage of valid programming language subsets and programming styles.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Another set of programs measure software metrics, to look for parts of the code that are likely to have mistakes.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] All the problems are fixed, or at least understood and double-checked.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Some code, such as digital filters, graphical user interfaces and inertial navigation systems, are so well understood that software tools have been developed to write the software.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] In these cases, specifications are developed and reliable software is produced automatically.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Unit test code is written to exercise every instruction of the code at least once to get 100% code coverage.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] A coverage tool is often used to verify that every instruction is executed, and then the test coverage is documented as well, for legal reasons.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] It forces detailed review of the program logic, and detects most coding, compiler and some design errors.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Some organizations write the unit tests *before* writing the code, using the software design as a module specification.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The unit test code is executed, and all the problems are fixed.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] As pieces of code become available, they are added to a skeleton of code, and tested in place to make sure each interface works.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Usually the built-in-tests of the electronics should be finished first, to begin burn-in and radio emissions tests of the electronics.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Next, the most important features of the software are integrated.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] At this stage, it is often beneficial for the integrators to have a way to run small, selected pieces of code, perhaps from a simple menu system.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Some program managers try to arrange this integration process so that after some minimal level of function is achieved, the system becomes deliverable at any following date, with increasing numbers of features as time passes.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Meanwhile, the test engineers usually begin assembling a test rig, and releasing preliminary tests for use by the software engineers.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] At some point, the tests cover all of the functions of the engineering specification.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] At this point, testing of the entire avionic unit begins.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The object of the acceptance testing is to prove that the unit is safe and reliable in operation.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The first test of the software, and one of the most difficult to meet in a tight schedule, is a realistic test of the unit's radio emissions.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] This usually must be started early in the project to assure that there is time to make any necessary changes to the design of the electronics.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The software is also subjected to a structural coverage analysis, where tests are run and code coverage is collected and analyzed.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] Each step produces a deliverable, either a document, code, or a test report.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] When the software passes all of its tests (or enough to be sold safely), these are bound into a certification report, that can literally have thousands of pages.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] The designated engineering representative, who has been striving for completion, then decides if the result is acceptable.
[src:do-178c/avionics-software] If it is, he signs it, and the avionic software is certified.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The term "avionics" was coined in 1949 by Philip J.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Klass, senior editor at *Aviation Week & Space Technology* magazine as a portmanteau of "**aviation electronics**".
[src:do-178c/avionics] Radio communication was first used in aircraft just prior to World War I.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The first airborne radios were in zeppelins, but the military sparked development of light radio sets that could be carried by heavier-than-air craft, so that aerial reconnaissance biplanes could report their observations immediately in case they were shot down.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The first experimental radio transmission from an airplane was conducted by the U.S.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The first aircraft radios transmitted by radiotelegraphy.
[src:do-178c/avionics] They required a two-seat aircraft with a second crewman who operated a telegraph key to spell out messages in Morse code.
[src:do-178c/avionics] During World War I, amplitude modulation voice two way radio sets were made possible in 1917 (see TM (triode)) by the development of the triode vacuum tube, which were simple enough that the pilot in a single seat aircraft could use it while flying.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Radar, the central technology used today in aircraft navigation and air traffic control, was developed by several nations, mainly in secret, as an air defense system in the 1930s during the runup to World War II.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Many modern avionics have their origins in World War II wartime developments.
[src:do-178c/avionics] For example, autopilot systems that are commonplace today began as specialized systems to help bomber planes fly steadily enough to hit precision targets from high altitudes.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Britain's 1940 decision to share its radar technology with its U.S. ally, particularly the magnetron vacuum tube, in the famous Tizard Mission, significantly shortened the war.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Modern avionics is a substantial portion of military aircraft spending.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Aircraft like the F-15E and the now retired F-14 have roughly 20 percent of their budget spent on avionics.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Most modern helicopters now have budget splits of 60/40 in favour of avionics.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The civilian market has also seen a growth in cost of avionics.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Flight control systems (fly-by-wire) and new navigation needs brought on by tighter airspaces, have pushed up development costs.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The major change has been the recent boom in consumer flying.
[src:do-178c/avionics] As more people begin to use planes as their primary method of transportation, more elaborate methods of controlling aircraft safely in these high restrictive airspaces have been invented.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Avionics plays a heavy role in modernization initiatives like the Federal Aviation Administration's (FAA) Next Generation Air Transportation System project in the United States and the Single European Sky ATM Research (SESAR) initiative in Europe.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The cockpit or, in larger aircraft, under the cockpit of an aircraft or in a movable nosecone, is a typical location for avionic bay equipment, including control, monitoring, communication, navigation, weather, and anti-collision systems.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The majority of aircraft power their avionics using 14- or 28‑volt DC electrical systems; however, larger, more sophisticated aircraft (such as airliners or military combat aircraft) have AC systems operating at 115 volts 400 Hz, AC.
[src:do-178c/avionics] International standards for avionics equipment are prepared by the Airlines Electronic Engineering Committee and published by ARINC.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Communications connect the flight deck to the ground and the flight deck to the passengers.
[src:do-178c/avionics] On‑board communications are provided by public-address systems and aircraft intercoms.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The VHF aviation communication system works on the airband of 118.000 MHz to 136.975 MHz.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Each channel is spaced from the adjacent ones by 8.33 kHz in Europe, 25 kHz elsewhere.
[src:do-178c/avionics] VHF is also used for line of sight communication such as aircraft-to-aircraft and aircraft-to-ATC.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Amplitude modulation is used, and the conversation is performed in simplex mode.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Aircraft communication can also take place using HF (especially for trans-oceanic flights) or satellite communication.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Air navigation is the determination of position and direction on or above the surface of the Earth.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Avionics can use satellite navigation systems (such as GPS, WAAS, EGNOS and GBAS/LAAS), inertial navigation system (INS), ground-based radio navigation systems (such as VOR or LORAN), or any combination thereof.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Some navigation systems such as GPS calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Older ground-based Navigation systems such as VOR or LORAN requires a pilot or navigator to plot the intersection of signals on a paper map to determine an aircraft's location; modern systems calculate the position automatically and display it to the flight crew on moving map displays.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The first hints of glass cockpits emerged in the 1970s when flight-worthy cathode ray tube (CRT) screens began to replace electromechanical displays, gauges and instruments.
[src:do-178c/avionics] A "glass" cockpit refers to the use of computer monitors instead of gauges and other analog displays.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Aircraft were getting progressively more displays, dials and information dashboards that eventually competed for space and pilot attention.
[src:do-178c/avionics] In the 1970s, the average aircraft had more than 100 cockpit instruments and controls.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Glass cockpits started to come into being with the Gulfstream G‑IV private jet in 1985.
[src:do-178c/avionics] One of the key challenges in glass cockpits is to balance how much control is automated and how much the pilot should do manually.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Generally they try to automate flight operations while keeping the pilot constantly informed.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Aircraft have means of automatically controlling flight.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Autopilot was first invented by Lawrence Sperry during World War I to fly bomber planes steady enough to hit accurate targets from 25,000 feet.
[src:do-178c/avionics] When it was first adopted by the U.S. military, a Honeywell engineer sat in the back seat with bolt cutters to disconnect the autopilot in case of emergency.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Nowadays most commercial planes are equipped with aircraft flight control systems in order to reduce pilot error and workload at landing or takeoff.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The first simple commercial auto-pilots were used to control heading and altitude and had limited authority on things like thrust and flight control surfaces.
[src:do-178c/avionics] In helicopters, auto-stabilization was used in a similar way.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The first systems were electromechanical.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The advent of fly-by-wire and electro-actuated flight surfaces (rather than the traditional hydraulic) has increased safety.
[src:do-178c/avionics] As with displays and instruments, critical devices that were electro-mechanical had a finite life.
[src:do-178c/avionics] With safety critical systems, the software is very strictly tested.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Fuel Quantity Indication System (FQIS) monitors the amount of fuel aboard.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Using various sensors, such as capacitance tubes, temperature sensors, densitometers & level sensors, the FQIS computer calculates the mass of fuel remaining on board.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Fuel Control and Monitoring System (FCMS) reports fuel remaining on board in a similar manner, but, by controlling pumps & valves, also manages fuel transfers around various tanks.
[src:do-178c/avionics] To supplement air traffic control, most large transport aircraft and many smaller ones use a traffic alert and collision avoidance system (TCAS), which can detect the location of nearby aircraft, and provide instructions for avoiding a midair collision.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Smaller aircraft may use simpler traffic alerting systems such as TPAS, which are passive (they do not actively interrogate the transponders of other aircraft) and do not provide advisories for conflict resolution.
[src:do-178c/avionics] To help avoid controlled flight into terrain (CFIT), aircraft use systems such as ground-proximity warning systems (GPWS), which use radar altimeters as a key element.
[src:do-178c/avionics] One of the major weaknesses of GPWS is the lack of "look-ahead" information, because it only provides altitude above terrain "look-down".
[src:do-178c/avionics] In order to overcome this weakness, modern aircraft use a terrain awareness warning system (TAWS).
[src:do-178c/avionics] Commercial aircraft cockpit data recorders, commonly known as "black boxes", store flight information and audio from the cockpit.
[src:do-178c/avionics] They are often recovered from an aircraft after a crash to determine control settings and other parameters during the incident.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Weather systems such as weather radar (typically Arinc 708 on commercial aircraft) and lightning detectors are important for aircraft flying at night or in instrument meteorological conditions, where it is not possible for pilots to see the weather ahead.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Heavy precipitation (as sensed by radar) or severe turbulence (as sensed by lightning activity) are both indications of strong convective activity and severe turbulence, and weather systems allow pilots to deviate around these areas.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Lightning detectors like the Stormscope or Strikefinder have become inexpensive enough that they are practical for light aircraft.
[src:do-178c/avionics] In addition to radar and lightning detection, observations and extended radar pictures (such as NEXRAD) are now available through satellite data connections, allowing pilots to see weather conditions far beyond the range of their own in-flight systems.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Modern displays allow weather information to be integrated with moving maps, terrain, and traffic onto a single screen, greatly simplifying navigation.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Modern weather systems also include wind shear and turbulence detection and terrain and traffic warning systems.
[src:do-178c/avionics] In‑plane weather avionics are especially popular in Africa, India, and other countries where air-travel is a growing market, but ground support is not as well developed.
[src:do-178c/avionics] There has been a progression towards centralized control of the multiple complex systems fitted to aircraft, including engine monitoring and management.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Health and usage monitoring systems (HUMS) are integrated with aircraft management computers to give maintainers early warnings of parts that will need replacement.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The integrated modular avionics concept proposes an integrated architecture with application software portable across an assembly of common hardware modules.
[src:do-178c/avionics] It has been used in fourth generation jet fighters and the latest generation of airliners.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Military aircraft have been designed either to deliver a weapon or to be the eyes and ears of other weapon systems.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The vast array of sensors available to the military is used for whatever tactical means required.
[src:do-178c/avionics] As with aircraft management, the bigger sensor platforms (like the E‑3D, JSTARS, ASTOR, Nimrod MRA4, Merlin HM Mk 1) have mission-management computers.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Police and EMS aircraft also carry sophisticated tactical sensors.
[src:do-178c/avionics] While aircraft communications provide the backbone for safe flight, the tactical systems are designed to withstand the rigors of the battlefield.
[src:do-178c/avionics] UHF, VHF Tactical (30–88 MHz) and SatCom systems combined with ECCM methods, and cryptography secure the communications.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Data links such as Link 11, 16, 22 and BOWMAN, JTRS and even TETRA provide the means of transmitting data (such as images, targeting information etc.).
[src:do-178c/avionics] Airborne radar was one of the first tactical sensors.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The benefit of altitude providing range has meant a significant focus on airborne radar technologies.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Radars include airborne early warning, anti-submarine warfare, and even weather radar (Arinc 708) and ground tracking/proximity radar.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The military uses radar in fast jets to help pilots fly at low levels.
[src:do-178c/avionics] While the civil market has had weather radar for a while, there are strict rules about using it to navigate the aircraft.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Dipping sonar fitted to a range of military helicopters allows the helicopter to protect shipping assets from submarines or surface threats.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Maritime support aircraft can drop active and passive sonar devices (sonobuoys) and these are also used to determine the location of enemy submarines.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Electro-optic systems include devices such as the head-up display (HUD), forward looking infrared (FLIR), infrared search and track and other passive infrared devices (Passive infrared sensor).
[src:do-178c/avionics] These are all used to provide imagery and information to the flight crew.
[src:do-178c/avionics] This imagery is used for everything from search and rescue to navigational aids and target acquisition.
[src:do-178c/avionics] Electronic support measures and defensive aids systems are used extensively to gather information about threats or possible threats.
[src:do-178c/avionics] They can be used to launch devices (in some cases automatically) to counter direct threats against the aircraft.
[src:do-178c/avionics] They are also used to determine the state of a threat and identify it.
[src:do-178c/avionics] The avionics systems in military, commercial and advanced models of civilian aircraft are interconnected using an avionics databus.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) applies DO-178B as the document it uses for guidance to determine if the software will perform reliably in an airborne environment, when specified by the Technical Standard Order (TSO) for which certification is sought.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] In the United States, the introduction of TSOs into the airworthiness certification process, and by extension DO-178B, is explicitly established in Title 14: Aeronautics and Space of the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR), also known as the Federal Aviation Regulations, Part 21, Subpart O.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] The failure conditions are categorized by their effects on the aircraft, crew, and passengers.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] DO-178B alone is not intended to guarantee software safety aspects.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Safety attributes in the design and implemented as functionality, must receive additional mandatory system safety tasks to drive and show objective evidence of meeting explicit safety requirements.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Typically IEEE STD-1228-1994 software safety plans are allocated and software safety analyses tasks are accomplished in sequential steps (requirements analysis, top level design analysis, detailed design analysis, code level analysis, test analysis and change analysis).
[src:do-178c/do-178b] These software safety tasks and artifacts are integral supporting parts of the process for hazard severity and DAL determination to be documented in system safety assessments (SSA).
[src:do-178c/do-178b] The certification authorities require and DO-178B specifies the correct DAL be established using these comprehensive analyses methods to establish the software level A-E.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Any software that commands, controls, and monitors safety-critical functions should receive the highest DAL - Level A.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] It is the software safety analyses that drive the system safety assessments that determine the DAL that drives the appropriate level of rigor in DO-178B.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Therefore, DO-178B central theme is design assurance and verification after the prerequisite safety requirements have been established.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] The number of objectives to be satisfied (eventually with independence) is determined by the software level A-E.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] The phrase "with independence" refers to a separation of responsibilities where the objectivity of the verification and validation processes is ensured by virtue of their "independence" from the software development team.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] For objectives that must be satisfied with independence, the person verifying the item (such as a requirement or source code) may not be the person who authored the item and this separation must be clearly documented.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] In some cases, an automated tool may be equivalent to independence.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] However, the tool itself must then be qualified if it substitutes for human review.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Processes are intended to support the objectives, according to the software level (A through D—Level E was outside the purview of DO-178B).
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Processes are described as abstract areas of work in DO-178B, and it is up to the planners of a real project to define and document the specifics of how a process will be carried out.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] On a real project, the actual activities that will be done in the context of a process must be shown to support the objectives.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] These activities are defined by the project planners as part of the Planning process.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] This objective-based nature of DO-178B allows a great deal of flexibility in regard to following different styles of software life cycle.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Once an activity within a process has been defined, it is generally expected that the project respect that documented activity within its process.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] Furthermore, processes (and their concrete activities) must have well defined entry and exit criteria, according to DO-178B, and a project must show that it is respecting those criteria as it performs the activities in the process.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] The flexible nature of DO-178B's processes and entry/exit criteria make it difficult to implement the first time, because these aspects are abstract and there is no "base set" of activities from which to work.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] The intention of DO-178B was not to be prescriptive.
[src:do-178c/do-178b] There are many possible and acceptable ways for a real project to define these aspects.
