[src:do-178c/do-178c] The certification authorities require and DO-178C specifies the correct DAL be established using these comprehensive analyses methods to establish the software level A-E.
[src:do-178c/do-178c] "The software level establishes the rigor necessary to demonstrate compliance" with DO-178C.
[src:do-178c/do-178c] The number of objectives to be satisfied (some with independence) is determined by the software level A-E.
[src:do-178c/do-178c] Processes are intended to support the objectives, according to the software level (A through D—Level E was outside the purview of DO-178C).
[src:do-178c/do-178c] Processes are described as abstract areas of work in DO-178C, and it is up to the planners of a real project to define and document the specifics of how a process will be carried out.
[src:do-178c/do-178c] This objective-based nature of DO-178C allows a great deal of flexibility in regard to following different styles of software life cycle.
[src:do-178c/do-178c] Furthermore, processes (and their concrete activities) must have well defined entry and exit criteria, according to DO-178C, and a project must show that it is respecting those criteria as it performs the activities in the process.
[src:do-178c/do-178c] The flexible nature of DO-178C's processes and entry/exit criteria make it difficult to implement the first time, because these aspects are abstract and there is no "base set" of activities from which to work.
